"Agent Orange Exposure and Gulf War Illness","Veterans concerned about Agent Orange exposure or Gulf War Illness can receive a VA military exposures health registry exam. ","<p>If you were exposed to <a href=""http://www.publichealth.va.gov/exposures/agentorange/"">Agent Orange</a> during the Vietnam War, you can receive an <a href=""http://www.publichealth.va.gov/exposures/agentorange/benefits/registry-exam.asp"">Agent Orange Registry health exam</a>.</p><br />
<p>If you’re concerned about <a href=""http://www.publichealth.va.gov/exposures/gulfwar/"">Gulf War Illness</a> from any duty from the first Gulf War through the Iraq War, you can receive a <a href=""http://www.publichealth.va.gov/exposures/gulfwar/benefits/registry-exam.asp"">Gulf War Registry health exam</a>.</p><br />
<p>These exams:</p><br />
<ul><li>are free</li><br />
<li>help identify possible long-term problems related to your service</li><br />
<li>don’t require enrollment in the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) health care system</li><br />
</ul><p>To register, contact your local <a href=""http://www.publichealth.va.gov/exposures/coordinators.asp"">VA environmental health care coordinator</a>.</p><br />
<p>To learn more, call the VA's Special Issues line at 1-800-749-8387 or visit <a href=""http://www.gulflink.osd.mil/"">GulfLINK</a>.</p><br />
